'''Walter Houston Clark''' (1902 - Dec 15, 1994) was a professor of [[psychology of religion]] at [[Andover Newton Theological School]]. He explored [[religion]], [[mystical experience]] and use of [[psychedelics]].
Clark was born in [[Westfield, New Jersey|Westfield, N.J.]]. He graduated from [[Williams College]] in 1928 and received a doctorate in psychology and education from [[Harvard University]] in 1944.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1994/12/21/obituaries/walter-clark-92-taught-psychology-of-religion.html Walter Clark, 92; Taught Psychology of Religion], ''[[New York Times]]''. Retrieved: 2017-10-04.</ref>
In 1962 he joined [[Harvard Psilocybin Project|Harvard Psychedelic Drug Project]]. Later he worked at the Worcester Foundation for Experimental Biology and at the Maryland Psychiatric Research Center at Spring Grove State Hospital investigating the effects of psychedelic drugs.<ref name="flashbaks">[[Leary, Timothy]]. "[[Flashbacks (book)|Flashbacks]]" (1983), p.101.</ref>
Clark was a co-founder and president of the Society for the Scientific Study of Religion. He received the [[American Psychological Association|APA Wlliam James Memorial Award]] for contributions to the [[psychology of religion]].<ref name="flashbaks" />
== Publications == ;Books * The Oxford Group: Its History and Significance (1951) * The Psychology of Religion (1958) * Chemical Ecstasy (1969) * Religious Experience: Its Nature and Function in the Human Psyche (1973)
