'''William Warrick Cardozo''' (1905–1962) was an [[African-American]] scientist who pioneered research on individuals suffering from [[sickle cell anemia]].<ref name="aetna.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.aetna.com/foundation/aahcalendar/1986cardozo.html|title=Aetna: African American History Calendar: 1986: William Warrick Cardozo|publisher=}}</ref>  He initially attended [[Hampton University]] and later [[Ohio State University]].<ref name="aaregistry.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.aaregistry.org/historic_events/view/sickle-cell-pioneer-willliam-w-cardozo|title=Sickle Cell Pioneer, William W. Cardozo – African American Registry|publisher=}}</ref> He was a medical doctor who worked primarily in [[Washington DC]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Dr. William Warrick Cardozo|date=1 November 1962|publisher=|journal=Journal of the National Medical Association|volume=54|issue=6|pages=723–724|via=PubMed Central|pmid=|pmc=2642202}}</ref>  He additionally worked on the development of African-American children as well as [[Hodgkin's disease]].<ref name="aetna.com"/> He died of a [[heart attack]].<ref name="aaregistry.org"/>

